1. Delight is not necessarily the emotion students of human misery would feel upon recognizing the sadness and futility; they might feel more somber or reflective.
2. The statement assumes that seeing the true extent of sadness would be a positive experience, which contradicts the nature of studying human misery.
3. Students of human misery may already be aware of the underlying sadness and futility, so there would be no new revelation to delight them.